  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published by Leuven University Press in 2022, \"Unfinished Histories\" shows promise in scholarly uptake, particularly noted by an engagement score indicating a strong commercial linkage through platforms like Amazon and Goodreads.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Unfinished Histories,\" released in 2022, has established a foothold within scholarly discourse, reflected in its 5 citations. Although the work shows limited engagement in broader public discussions, its commercial linkage through major platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads highlights potential interest outside academic circles. This commercial visibility may serve as a pathway for further academic and public engagement.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The current usage landscape for \"Unfinished Histories\" appears sparse, with no available metrics indicating online mentions or discussions on platforms traditionally associated with community discourse, such as Wikipedia or Reddit. This absence suggests that while the work has begun to find its niche in academia, it may not yet resonate fully with a larger audience seeking insights on historical narratives.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the limited outreach, the work's scholarly uptake signifies a kernel of academic validation that may evolve over time. The citations, while modest, underscore an emerging interest that could indicate the groundwork for future discourse and academic exploration surrounding the themes addressed in the book. This incremental uptake is not unusual for scholarly works that often take time to permeate academic discussions.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In conclusion, while \"Unfinished Histories\" has not yet achieved significant online engagement or recognition across community platforms, its initial citation metrics reflect a nascent scholarly footprint. As the work continues to be explored, it has the potential to contribute to ongoing conversations in the field, possibly leading to broader societal relevance and academic impact in the years to come.</p>",
